@DATABASE "TRW Documentation"

@NODE MAIN "TRW Documentation"

                          Introduction

TRW  is  something that a lot of people have been wanting for DLG
for  a long time: a visually-oriented sysop utility to manage his
or  her DLG configuration without trudging through the normal DLG
configuration  module.    Its intended goal is to totally replace
the  functionality  of  the  DLG native configuration program and
then  some.    Almost  every  aspect of this program will feature
improvements  above and beyond the capabilities of the DLG config
program.  For  instance,  in the @{" File Area manager " Link File_Area_manager}, you will be
able  to  move  or  copy  file areas, or create file areas from a
common  template.    Little things like this should make your DLG
sysopping more enjoyable.

@{" General " Link General}
@{" Setting it up " Link Setting_it_up}
@{" Navigating the Program " Link Navigating_the_Program}
@{" Last Words " Link Last_Words}
@{" Glossary " Link Glossary}
@ENDNODE

@NODE General "General"
@{" TRW " Link TRW}
@{" Disclaimers and other stuff " Link Disclaimers_and_other_stuff}
@{" Shareware " Link Shareware}
@ENDNODE

@NODE TRW "TRW"
                            About TRW

Three cryptic initials might be a fun topic to keep folks
guessing from now until the return of @{" Zar-Quon " Link Zar-Quon}, but I'll make it
easy.  It stands for "The Right Way," and is the summation of my
opinion of how a config program SHOULD work.

I could spend a few moments trying to convince you why you should
use TRW, but I think after a few minutes playing with it, you'll
know exactly why.  Being a DLG sysop myself, I've often been
discouraged by the complexity of the system and a lack of a
common tie between the different elements.  The complexity gives
us great freedom, but also makes our jobs difficult at times.
Computers are great at reducing complexities down to a few key
elements, given the right program.  I think this is the right
program.  And if someone disagrees, I enthusiastically urge them
to prove me wrong... it's a win-win situation, IMO.  :-)

@ENDNODE

