@NODE Technical_Support "Technical Support"
                     You brave person, you!

This being @{" beta " Link beta} software, it is essential to the process that I
receive timely and accurate bug reports.  It is in public beta
status for the purpose of getting feedback in quantity from as
wide a cross-section as possible.

All bugs will be promptly investigated and stomped if needed.
Really serious bugs will be addressed in the form of an interim
release between versions.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Shareware "Shareware"
                      The Shareware Concept

When all is said and done, TRW will be released as a shareware
program.  However, it will not be a disabled shareware -- at
most, it will have a delay at startup.  I don't expect to get
rich from it, but who does?  :-)

This may change, in that I may decide to make it giftware or
something like that, but I will NOT be releasing anything that's
crippled.  Annoying, maybe.  But not crippled.  So rest easy...
and save the flames for the really important subjects, like one's
choice in ANSI screens :-)

@ENDNODE

@NODE Setting_it_up "Setting it up"
@{" ReqTools.Library " Link ReqTools.Library}
@{" System Requirments " Link System_Requirments}
@ENDNODE

@NODE ReqTools.Library "ReqTools.Library"
I have set version 38 of @{" ReqTools " Link ReqTools} as the baseline for use
with TRW.  Version 38 was distributed in the ReqTools 2.2B
archive.  The version archived with TRW is the current latest
version, but will always be at least version 38.  If it is newer
than your version, copy it to your LIBS: directory.

@ENDNODE

@NODE System_Requirments "System Requirments"
      What's needed:

   o  DLG version 1.0 must be up and running.

   o  @{" ReqTools " Link ReqTools} version 38 must be installed.

   o  AmigaDOS 2.04 or later must be in use.

   o  Stack size of 40000.  If you use the supplied icon,
      you need not worry about this.  If you launch it from CLI
      or another program (such as ToolManager) you will need to
      set your stack in the appropriate place.

         That's about it!

@ENDNODE

@NODE Navigating_the_Program "Navigating the Program"
                         Getting around

Moving around in TRW is simple: click your mouse buttons and
you're off!  When TRW starts up, you are deposited in the main
screen, from where you can select your destination.

Discussion of TRW's controls will be based on each of the
different screens available to you.

@{" Main Screen " Link Main_Screen}
@{" File Area Manager " Link File_Area_Manager}
@ENDNODE

