@NODE <<<_(Select_file_area) "<<< (Select file area)"
      Brings up a requestor that allows you to choose what file
      area is the current file area.  If the current file area
      has users in it, you will not be able to enter the file
      area manager.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Quit "Quit"
This causes TRW to clean up and exit.  In the Main screen, there
are no existing locks and anything loaded into memory has already
been saved.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Status_Indicators "Status Indicators"
@{" Status " Link Status}
@{" Current File Area " Link Current_File_Area}
@{" (Current File Area) Users " Link (Current_File_Area)_Users}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Status "Status"
Various and sundry bits of information appear here. If something
goes wrong, there will probably be a note here.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Current_File_Area "Current File Area"
   This displays the number and name of the current file area. On
   startup, TRW defaults to the very first file area as current.
   If you select a different file area while in the file area
   manager, that area will be the current file area until you
   change it or quit the program.  You can use the "<<<" gadget
   next to this display to change the current file area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE (Current_File_Area)_Users "(Current File Area) Users"
   This displays the number of users in the current file area. If
   there area any users in the current file area, you cannot
   enter the file area manager, and its button will be ghosted.
   To change file areas, select the "<<<" gadget next to this
   display.


@ENDNODE

@NODE File_Area_Manager "File Area Manager"
                      The File Area Manager

This screen allows you to configure your file areas as you wish.
All actions operate on the CURRENT file area.

When you enter this screen, the program immediately tries to get
an @{" exclusive lock " Link exclusive_lock} on the very first file area listed.  If it
cannot, you will get the busy pointer until that file area
becomes freed.  The most common cause of this problem is if a
user is in that file area.  Solution: kick the user out!  Once
all users are out of the target area, it will be locked via DLG.
It will be released when you go to another area or leave the file
area manager.

@{" File Areas Gadget " Link File_Areas_Gadget}
@{" Add Area " Link Add_Area}
@{" Edit Name " Link Edit_Name}
@{" Delete Area " Link Delete_Area}
@{" Move Area " Link Move_Area}
@{" Copy Area " Link Copy_Area}
@{" Access Levels " Link Access_Levels}
@{" Print Report " Link Print_Report}
@{" Templates " Link Templates}
@{" Merge Areas " Link Merge_Areas}
@{" SIGs " Link SIGs}
@{" Auto-Access " Link Auto-Access}
@{" Fido (Tick) " Link Fido_(Tick)}
@{" Alt Path " Link Alt_Path}
@{" Signatures " Link Signatures}
@{" Freq-Able " Link Freq-Able}
@{" Validation Required " Link Validation_Required}
@{" Save " Link Save}
@{" Return to Main " Link Return_to_Main}
@{" Quit " Link Quit}
@{" Status " Link Status}
@ENDNODE

@NODE File_Areas_Gadget "File Areas Gadget"
This gadget allows you to select the file area on which to
operate.  The number and the name of the file area are displayed
here.  The currently selected file area is displayed in the
gadget on the bottom.

When you select a file area, TRW will attempt to gain an
@{" exclusive lock " Link exclusive_lock} on the file area.  Until it does, you will see a
busy pointer.  See above about entering the manager -- it is
exactly the same thing.  Get that user outta there, and you're
fine.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Add_Area "Add Area"
Hitting this button starts you on a series of requestors asking
you for the name and number of the file area, and gives you the
choice to set up various flags for that file area.

Once a file area is created, you have the option of automatically
updating all users' global file list if it is an auto-access area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Edit_Name "Edit Name"
Simply change the name of the current file area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Delete_Area "Delete Area"
Deletes the CURRENT file area, updating user global file info in
the process.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Move_Area "Move Area"
Allows you to renumber the file area to something else,
effectively moving it.  TRW will automatically sort the file
areas and re-select the "new" file area for you.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Copy_Area "Copy Area"
Allows you to copy a file area into a new file area. The new file
area will be identical in all ways to the current file area,
except the number (which CANNOT be duplicated) and the file area
name (which does NOT have to be changed but would be confusing
otherwise).

After creating the file area, you have the option of copying the
files in that area over.  This takes a while!

@ENDNODE

@NODE Access_Levels "Access Levels"
Change the upload, download, and other access level flags for the
current file area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Print_Report "Print Report"
Prints a report of your file areas.  You can either print to a
file of your choosing, or output to your current preferences
printer.

The output looks like this:

Area Name                           Red  AFVS ACC  UL  DL KIL XFR SYS Path
==== ============================== ==== ==== === === === === === === =======
   1 Archivers                        99 1110   1  20   1 255  30 255
                                              255 255 255 255 255 255

  10 Tester                           99 1110   1  20   1 255  30 255
                                              255 255 255 255 255 255

==== ============================== ==== ==== === === === === === === =======


The fields are arranged thus:

   o  Area -   The file area number.
   o  Name -   The name of the file area.
   o  Red  -   If the file area requires validation, this is the
               file area that the files will be redirected to.
   o  AFVS -   The four file area flags.  They are:

               A - Auto-Access
               F - Freqable
               V - Validation Required
               S - Signatures

               If set to a "1", it is active.  If set to a "0",
               it is inactive.
   o  ACC  -   Auto-Access level.  The number on top is the low
               access level, the bottom number is the upper
               access level.  The following five fields are
               arranged in the same manner.
   o  UL   -   Upload access levels
   o  DL   -   Download access level
   o  KIL  -   Kill access level
   o  XFR  -   Transfer Access Level
   o  SYS  -   Sysop access level
   o  Path -   The alternate file storage path.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Templates "Templates"
         This feature is not yet implemented.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Merge_Areas "Merge Areas"
         This feature is not yet implemented.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SIGs "SIGs"
         This feature is not yet implemented.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Auto-Access "Auto-Access"
This checkbox gadget allows you to turn on and off the
auto-access level for the current file area.  If turning it on,
you get a requestor asking for the access levels.  The last
access levels entered are kept even if you deactivate this flag,
so if they are satisfactory you can just hit return.  If this
file area has never been auto-access, the default levels are 1
and 255.

You can also change the upper and lower access level at any given
time by simply putting the cursor in the appropriate box and
changing the number.  The Auto-Access checkbox must be activated
in order for this to be possible.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Fido_(Tick) "Fido (Tick)"
          This feature is not yet implemented..

@ENDNODE

@NODE Alt_Path "Alt Path"
Two gadgets are presented to you; the first gadget is a string
gadget in which you may enter the path to an alternate file
storage location.

NOTE: The total length of the path must be less than 8 characters
      long.  I know, this is pretty useless, but talk to @{" TpT " Link TpT},
      not me :-)  At any rate, TRW won't let you get away with
      it, so don't try :-)

The second gadget brings up a file path requestor that allows you
to select from any existing paths you wish. Once again, limit the
full path info to less than 8 characters in length.  Hitting
CANCEL will return you to the original value; hitting OKAY
without selecting anything will return the original value, too.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Signatures "Signatures"
This checkbox controls whether the current file area allows
signatures or not.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Freq-Able "Freq-Able"
This flag controls whether the file area is @{" freq " Link freq}-able or not.
Your file request server should honor this flag, as well as any
file list makers you use.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Validation_Required "Validation Required"
If this is on, all files uploaded to the current file area will
require validation before anyone can see them to download them.
When turning this option on, you are automatically presented with
a File Redirection requestor showing a list of file areas.

If the checkbox is active, you can change the area at any given
time by simply changing the number in the "To Area ..." Box.

In either case, the program checks to make sure the file area
actually exists.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Save "Save"
Saves all file area information. It may take a while, so be
patient.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Return_to_Main "Return to Main"
Returns you to the @{" main screen " Link main_screen} after releasing the `exclusive
lock' on the current file area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Quit "Quit"
Exits TRW.  There is no option to save or not save info on the
way out.  The reason for this is simple: many functions (add
area, auto-access) already have written partial information to
the @{" hard drive " Link hard_drive}, such as creating a directory or changing the
global file area lists.  Because of this, the current information
is saved.  It's better to have a full coherent save of an
undesireable configuration than it is to have a partial save that
could crash your BBS.

Before exiting, TRW releases the @{" exclusive lock " Link exclusive_lock} on the current
file area.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Status "Status"
Displays various information as the program operates. If an error
occurs, look here for a clue.  During long operations, watch this
for progressive status of the operation.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Last_Words "Last Words"
@{" Future plans " Link Future_plans}
@{" Tools of the Trade " Link Tools_of_the_Trade}
@ENDNODE

@NODE Future_plans "Future plans"
Early development of this program will be as a public @{" beta " Link beta}.
This is for the purpose of collecting as much information as I
can about bugs, on as many different systems as possible.

Once TRW 1.0 is released and all bugs are definately stomped, I
don't think there will be much to add to TRW that I am not
already thinking of doing.  Keep the suggestions coming, of
course.  A really GOOD suggestion will get a new version out
there :-)

However, at some point it will reach my intended goal and I'll
move on to other things.  My next few projects are all aimed at
DLG with two exceptions.  One idea is to write my own mail
software for DLG.

So, we have a lot of work to do.  First things first.  I hope you
like TRW and see some potential in it.  Enjoy yourself!

@ENDNODE

