AmiNet is a series of Internet FTP sites that mirror each other
in order to maintain a rich, full file database of Amiga
software.  I need a good list of sites for this paragraph.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Backups "Backups"
                          About Backups

An archaiac term referring to making a copy of one's valuable
data onto a seperate medium to be kept against a time of
emergency, such as rampant shareware eating one's @{" hard drive " Link hard_drive}.  I
personally prefer a very excellent program called MRBackup, but
your weapon of choice may be different.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Beta "Beta"
                   The mysterious term, "Beta"

A software euphamism for "EXTREMELY DANGEROUS!"

@ENDNODE

@NODE Coffee "Coffee"
                       In Praise of Coffee

         It is by coffee alone I put my mind in motion.
     It is by the beans of Java that thoughts acquire speed.
      The hands acquire shaking, the shaking is a warning.
         It is by coffee alone I put my mind in motion.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DaRP "DaRP"
                           About DaRP

This is one of the projects of the DLG Resource Project, or DaRP.
DaRP is a project in itself, patterned after ARP. It's both an
homage to the original ARP creators, and a two-edged comment
about DLG in general.  If DLG weren't so flexible, DaRP would not
be possible.  However, if DLG were more in line with what a lot
of sysops want or need, DaRP wouldn't have a reason for being.
Hopefully, everyone will see the half-full version, not the
half-empty.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Exclusive_Lock "Exclusive Lock"
                      About Exclusive Locks

There are two ways that this term might be used.

The first, and more common reference, relates to the ability of
Amiga DOS functions to gain access to a file and allow no other
program to use it.  This is considered bad form in programming
circles, but it happens.

The second reference is related to DLG.  In DLG, a program can
gain access to a file or message area exclusively, disallowing
users to get into an area.  However, if a user is already in
there, you won't get access to it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Freq "Freq"
                          Freq-ing Out!

FREQ is an acronym for File REQuest, a FidoNet method of getting
files from a BBS without logging on.  Both ends of the link must
be using a FTN front-end, such as TrapDoor, and one end must be
running a File Request Server, which fetches the requested files
and sends them to the requester.

In DLG, a file area that is FREQ-able will contain files that you
don't mind sharing.  Some file areas may contain files that you
wish to restrict, such as X-rated GIFs or whatnot, and you would
not want that file area to be accessable outside the controlled
environment of the BBS.

@ENDNODE

